04376nmm a2200685Ia 9781501703539DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979581439  a97815017035397 a10.7591/97815017035392doi  a(DE-B1597)478478  a(OCoLC)950738868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS374.R47bD68 201704a813.54093822231 aDouglas, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIf God Meant to Interfere :bAmerican Literature and the Rise of the Christian Right /cChristopher Douglas. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (378 p.) :b2 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rise of the Christian Right took many writers and literary critics by surprise, trained as we were to think that religions waned as societies became modern. In If God Meant to Interfere, Christopher Douglas shows that American writers struggled to understand and respond to this new social and political force. Religiously inflected literature since the 1970s must be understood in the context of this unforeseen resurgence of conservative Christianity, he argues, a resurgence that realigned the literary and cultural fields.Among the writers Douglas considers are Marilynne Robinson, Barbara Kingsolver, Cormac McCarthy, Thomas Pynchon, Ishmael Reed, N. Scott Momaday, Gloria Anzaldúa, Philip Roth, Carl Sagan, and Dan Brown. Their fictions engaged a wide range of topics: religious conspiracies, faith and wonder, slavery and imperialism, evolution and extraterrestrial contact, alternate histories and ancestral spiritualities. But this is only part of the story. Liberal-leaning literary writers responding to the resurgence were sometimes confused by the Christian Right’s strange entanglement with the contemporary paradigms of multiculturalism and postmodernism —leading to complex emergent phenomena that Douglas terms "Christian multiculturalism" and "Christian postmodernism." Ultimately, If God Meant to Interfere shows the value of listening to our literature for its sometimes subterranean attention to the religious and social upheavals going on around it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literaturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChristianity in literature. 0aEvangelicalism in literature. 0aFundamentalism in literature. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aReligious Studies.  aFundamentalism, Evangelicalism, Postmodernism, Multiculturalism, Religious Right.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170353940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703539/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016